THE WORLD 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Former Philippine President Ferdinand E. Marcos has suffered liver failure and 
the prognosis is "extremely poor," a hospital administrator said. "Mr. Marcos 
is semi-comatose, his condition has worsened and he's not recognizing friends 
or family," said Eugene Tiwanak, assistant administrator of St. Francis Medical 
Center in Honolulu, where the exiled former leader has been hospitalized five 
months. Marcos suffered heart, lung and kidney failure late last month, and he 
has been on life-support equipment since. Marcos, 71, and his wife, Imelda, 
have lived in Hawaii since a 1986 popular revolt catapulted Corazon Aquino to 
the presidency, ending his 20-year rule. 
</P>
