<HEADLINE>
<P>
SAN GABRIEL VALLEY DIGEST: BALDWIN PARK; 
</P>
<P>
COUNCIL HANDLES SHORTFALL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
To make up a $260,700 shortfall in the 1989-90 city budget, the City Council 
has approved three belt-tightening moves, City Clerk Linda Gair said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
At a meeting last week, the City Council voted to eliminate the entire 
six-member code enforcement division, saving $260,300, Gair said. The 
division's work, including enforcement of weed-abatement laws and issuance of 
city licenses, are being absorbed by other city departments, she said. 
</P>
<P>
The council also reallocated money from two other sources to make up the 
deficit. Gair said the city will save $25,000 on lower liability insurance 
premiums, and $28,400 will be transferred from the city's retirement fund 
surplus. 
</P>
<P>
Mayor Leo King said the staff cutbacks were necessary to keep the city 
financially afloat. "We were getting to the point where we were borrowing from 
Peter to pay Paul." He said the code enforcement division was top-heavy with 
supervisors and its work could be performed by other departments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
