<P>
HOME SALES RISE ON LOWER INTEREST 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times wire services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WASHINGTON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Sales of new homes edged up 2.7% in May as mortgage interest rates continued to 
decline, but they remained well behind the pace set in the previous two years, 
the government reported today. 
</P>
<P>
The Commerce Department said sales of new single-family homes rose to a 
seasonally adjusted annual rate of 613,000 units in May following a 9.1% 
increase in April. The April figure was revised downward from the 10.9% 
increase reported earlier. 
</P>
<P>
The April increase had been attributed by some economists to an aberration in 
sales in February and March, when sales dropped 11.3% and 11.9%, respectively. 
Sales had risen 4.6% in January. 
</P>
<P>
The pace of sales in May still was well behind the 676,000 new homes sold in 
1988 and the 671,000 units sold in 1987. 
</P>
</TEXT>
